 played at both professional and international levels as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]].\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Robertinho played club football in Brazil, Portugal and Switzerland for [[Fluminense Football Club|Fluminense]], [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo|Flamengo]], [[Sociedade Esportiva Palmeiras|Palmeiras]], [[Sport Club Internacional|Internacional]], [[Sport Club do Recife|Sport Recife]], [[Clube Atl\u00e9tico Mineiro|Atl\u00e9tico Mineiro]], [[C.D. Nacional|Nacional]] and Gr\u00f6ssembacher.<ref name=\"nft\">{{NFT player|id=30771|accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foradejogo.net/player.php?player=196006220001|title=Profile|language=Portuguese|publisher=Fora de Jogo}}</ref>\n\nHe earned one international cap for [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] on 25 September 1980, against Paraguay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sambafoot.com/en/trainers/516_robertinho.html|title=Profile|publisher=Sambafoot}}</ref>\n\nRobertinho became manager of Tunisian club [[Stade Tunisien]] for the second time in September 2007; he had previously coached Brazilian clubs [[Americano Futebol Clube|Americano]] and [[Fluminense Football Club|Fluminense]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/7016474.stm|title=Robertinho to coach Stade Tunisien|date=27 September 2007|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FootballDatabase.eu|95796--robertinho}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Robertinho managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{Brasil de Pelotas managers}}\n{{Esporte Clube S\u00e3o Bento managers}}\n{{Fluminense Football Club managers}}\n{{Centro Sportivo Alagoano managers}}\n{{Clube de Regatas Brasil managers}}\n{{America Football Club managers}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robertinho}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rio de Janeiro (city)]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Angola]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Rwanda]]\n[[Category:Brazil international footballers]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A players]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A managers]]\n[[Category:Fluminense FC players]]\n[[Category:Clube de Regatas do Flamengo footballers]]\n[[Category:Sociedade Esportiva Palmeiras players]]\n[[Category:Sport Club Internacional players]]\n[[Category:Sport Club do Recife players]]\n[[Category:Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas players]]\n[[Category:Clube Atl\u00e9tico Mineiro players]]\n[[Category:C.D. Nacional players]]\n[[Category:Rio Branco Esporte Clube managers]]\n[[Category:Esporte Clube Pelotas managers]]\n[[Category:Esporte Clube S\u00e3o Bento managers]]\n[[Category:Fluminense FC managers]]\n[[Category:Clube de Regatas Brasil managers]]\n[[Category:Centro Sportivo Alagoano managers]]\n[[Category:America Football Club (RJ) managers]]\n[[Category:Rio Branco Atl\u00e9tico Clube managers]]\n[[Category:Stade Tunisien managers]]\n[[Category:Kazma SC managers]]\n[[Category:Al-Shamal SC managers]]\n[[Category:Legi\u00e3o Futebol Clube managers]]\n[[Category:Stade Gab\u00e8sien managers]]\n[[Category:ES Hammam-Sousse managers]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Sport Avia\u00e7\u00e3o managers]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update FootballDatabase.eu template, misc formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robertinho"}
{"title_page": "J\u00e9ssica de la Pe\u00f1a", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2011}}\n{{orphan|date=September 2011}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = J\u00e9ssica de la Pe\u00f1a\n| image = J\u00e9ssicaNews.jpg\n| caption = J\u00e9ssica de la Pe\u00f1a\n| birth_name = J\u00e9ssica Annais de La Pe\u00f1a Camargo\n| birth_date = c. {{Birth year and age|1977}}\n| birth_place = {{flag | United States}} [[New York City]], [[United States]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = Colombian & American\n| education = Social Communication and Journalism\n| occupation = Journalist, news reporter\n| years_active= 22\n| agent = \n| title = \n| religion = \n| relatives = \n| family = Ernesto Chalela\n| children = Luna Chalela De La Pe\u00f1a\n| website = \n| alias = \n| spouse = \n| domestic_partner =\n| ethnicity = \n| credits = TVyNovelas Colombia Award \n}}\n\n'''J\u00e9ssica Annais de la Pe\u00f1a Camargo''' ([[New York]], [[November 13]] of [[1977]]) is a [[presenter]] and [[Journalism/journalist]] [[Colombian]].\n\n== Biography ==\nJ\u00e9ssica Annais de La Pe\u00f1a Camargo was born in [[New York City|New York]], and at the age of five she migrated to [[Barranquilla]] with her parents Ricardo de la Pe\u00f1a and Cecilia Camargo, and her sister. She completed her academic studies at the ''Colegio El Buen Consejo'' in Barranquilla, and graduated in Social Communication and Journalism from the ''Universidad del Norte'', in the same city. Her most notable passions include dancing and singing. Her first casting for presenter she did in second half. At age 20, while in the second semester of her university career, she auditioned to enter a program at her university, but thanks to her excellent record in cameras, she entered the regional channel ''[[Telecaribe]]'', where she first presented a variety program called ''La Noche'' and the ''Televista'' newscast. A year later, she was hired by ''Noticias RCN'' as presenter of the weekend editions, work that she alternated for seven months with her university studies and Telecaribe. After that time, she settled completely in Bogot\u00e1, where she went to present weekly broadcasts of the newscast. She transferred her career to the [[Pontifical Xavierian University|Javeriana University]] so as not to delay her studies in the last semester.\n\n== Personal life ==\nJessica had a relationship with a singer from Valledupar, Peter Manjarr\u00e9s, from 2008 to 2010. She was the inspiration for his song, ''Tragao de t\u00ed''.  Unfortunately, their relationship didn't last long.<ref>[http://www.blogvallenato.com/2010/02/peter-manjarres-termino-con-jessica-de-la-pena/ Jessica and Peter finished their romance]</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Jessica started a new relationship with an engineer called Andres Jaramillo. In April, 2017 Jessica married businessman Ernesto Chalela.<ref>[http://www.elrunrun.net/nuevo-novio-de-jessica-de-la-pena/ We'll introduce you. Meet Jessica De La Pe\u00f1a's new boyfriend. The Run Run, September 16, 2015]</ref> On September 19, 2017 he announced through Instagram the birth of his first daughter.\n\n== Career ==\n* '''''Televista News''''': The Regional News informs viewers of local, and international Caribbean national events,\n* '''''RCN News''''': She was anchorwoman of different editions of the newsreel between 1998 and 2016. In May, Jessica announced that she would travel to the United States to be a news correspondent for the RCN in New York and other cities of the country.<ref>[http://www.canalrcn.com/exclusivas/videos/articulo-video/jessica-de-la-pena-se-despide-del-canal-rcn-exclusivas-6427/ Jessica de la Pe\u00f1a says goodbye to the RCN Channel. In Exclusive, Canal RCN, May 14, 2016]</ref>\n\n== Trajectory ==\n* ''The Night'', by [[Telecaribe]] (1997)\n* '' Televista News'', by [[Telecaribe]] (1997-1998)\n* ''[[RCN News]]' (1998- ... )\n* ''[[Breakfast]]'' (2018- ... )\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat-inline}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pena, Jessica}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Colombian journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Barranquilla]]\n\n\n{{US-journalist-1970s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{cleanup translation|Spanish|date=May 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2011}}\n{{orphan|date=September 2011}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = J\u00e9ssica de la Pe\u00f1a\n| image = J\u00e9ssicaNews.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_name = J\u00e9ssica Annais de La Pe\u00f1a Camargo\n| birth_date = c. {{Birth year and age|1977}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], United States\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = Colombian American\n| education = \n| occupation = Journalist, news reporter\n| years_active= \n| agent = \n| title = \n| religion = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| family = \n| website = \n| alias = \n| spouse = \n| domestic_partner =\n| ethnicity = \n| credits = \n}}\nJ\u00e9ssica Annais de La Pe\u00f1a Camargo was born in [[New York City|New York]], and at the age of five she migrated to [[Barranquilla]] with her parents Ricardo de la Pe\u00f1a and Cecilia Camargo, and her sister. She completed her academic studies at the ''Colegio El Buen Consejo'' in Barranquilla, and graduated in Social Communication and Journalism from the ''Universidad del Norte'', in the same city. Her most notable passions include dancing and singing. Her first casting for presenter she did in second half. At age 20, while in the second semester of her university career, she auditioned to enter a program at her university, but thanks to her excellent record in cameras, she entered the regional channel ''[[Telecaribe]]'', where she first presented a variety program called ''La Noche'' and the ''Televista'' newscast. A year later, she was hired by ''Noticias RCN'' as presenter of the weekend editions, work that she alternated for seven months with her university studies and Telecaribe. After that time, she settled completely in Bogot\u00e1, where she went to present weekly broadcasts of the newscast. She transferred her career to the [[Pontifical Xavierian University|Javeriana University]] so as not to delay her studies in the last semester.\n\n== Personal life ==\nJessica had a relationship with a singer from Valledupar, Peter Manjarr\u00e9s, from 2008 to 2010. She was the inspiration for his song, ''Tragao de t\u00ed''.  Unfortunately, their relationship did not last long.<ref>[http://www.blogvallenato.com/2010/02/peter-manjarres-termino-con-jessica-de-la-pena/ J\u00e9ssica y Peter terminar\u00f3n su romance]</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Jessica started a new relationship with an engineer called Andres Jaramillo. In April, 2017 Jessica married businessman Ernesto Chalela.<ref>[http://www.elrunrun.net/nuevo-novio-de-jessica-de-la-pena/ Te lo presentamos. Conoce al nuevo novio de Jessica De La Pe\u00f1a. El Run Run, 16 de septiembre de 2015]</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n* '''''Televista News''''': The Regional News informs viewers of local, and international Caribbean national events,\n* '''''RCN News''''': She was anchorwoman of different editions of the newsreel between 1998 and 2016. In May, Jessica announced that she would travel to the United States to be a news correspondent for the RCN in New York and other cities of the country.<ref>[http://www.canalrcn.com/exclusivas/videos/articulo-video/jessica-de-la-pena-se-despide-del-canal-rcn-exclusivas-6427 Jessica de la Pe\u00f1a se despide del Canal RCN. En Exclusiva, Canal RCN, 14 de mayo de 2016]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat-inline}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pena, Jessica}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Colombian journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Barranquilla]]\n\n\n{{US-journalist-1970s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Yel Martinez Seo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Expand content, translate content that was in Spanish, place references (they were already in the document)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C3%A9ssica_de_la_Pe%C3%B1a"}
{"title_page": "Fanta", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Short description|Brand of carbonated drinks}} \n{{Use American English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox Beverage\n|name= Fanta\n|image= File:Logo Fanta 2016.png\n|caption= \n|manufacturer= [[The Coca-Cola Company]]\n|origin= [[Germany]] (beverage)<!-- Not \"Nazi\", see [[Talk:Fanta|Fanta talk page]]. --><br />[[Italy]] (orange version)\n|headquarters= \n|introduced= {{start date and age|1940}}\n|variants= See [[Fanta#International availability|International availability]]\n|related= [[Sunkist (soft drink)|Sunkist]], [[Crush (soft drink)|Crush]], [[Slice (soft drink)|Slice]], [[Mirinda]], [[Tango (drink)|Tango]], [[Bluna]].\n}}\n\n'''Fanta''' is a brand of fruit-flavored carbonated drinks created by [[The Coca-Cola Company|Coca-Cola Deutschland]] under the leadership of German businessman [[Max Keith]]. There are more than [[International availability of Fanta|100 flavors worldwide]]. Fanta originated as a [[Coca-Cola]] substitute during the American [[trade embargo]] of [[Nazi Germany]] which affected the availability of Coca-Cola ingredients in 1940; the current version was created in Italy. The name Fanta is a shortening of the word Fantasie (German for fantasy).\n\n==Origin in Germany==\n[[File:FantaKlassik.JPG|thumb|upright|75th anniversary release of Fanta in Germany]]\n\nDuring the [[World War II|Second World War]], the US established a trade embargo against [[Germany]]\u2014making the export of [[Coca-Cola]] syrup difficult.<ref name=\"a\">{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/cokelore/fanta.asp |title=The Reich Stuff? |author=Mikkelson, Barbara |date=April 29, 2011 |work=[[Snopes]] |publisher= |accessdate=March 11, 2012}}</ref> To circumvent this, [[Max Keith]], the head of Coca-Cola Deutschland (Coca-Cola GmbH), decided to create a new product for the German market, using only ingredients available in Germany at the time, including [[beet sugar]], [[whey]], and apple [[pomace]]\u2014the \"leftovers of leftovers\", as Keith later recalled.<ref name=\"a\" /><ref name=\"pendergrast\">[[Mark Pendergrast]]: For God, Country and Coca-Cola, Charles Scribner's Sons, New York, 1993</ref> The name was the result of a brainstorming session, which started with Keith's exhorting his team to \"use their imagination\" (''Fantasie'' in German), to which one of his salesmen, Joe Knipp, retorted \"Fanta!\".<ref name=\"pendergrast\" />\n\nThe plant was cut off from Coca-Cola headquarters during the war. After the war, The Coca-Cola Company regained control of the plant, formula, and the trademarks to the new Fanta product\u2014as well as the plant profits made during the war.<ref name=a /><ref name=\"pendergrast\" />\n\nIn 1943 alone, 3 million cases of Fanta were sold. Many bottles were not drunk, but used to add sweetness and flavor to soups and stews, since wartime sugar was severely rationed.<ref name=a /><ref name=\"pendergrast\" />\n\nDuring the war the Dutch Coca-Cola plant in [[Amsterdam]] (N.V. Nederlandsche Coca-Cola Maatschappij) suffered the same difficulties as the German Coca-Cola plant. Max Keith put the Fanta brand at the disposal of the Dutch Coca-Cola plant, of which he had been appointed the official caretaker. Dutch Fanta had a different recipe from German Fanta, [[Elderberry|elderberries]] being one of the main ingredients.<ref>[http://peterzwaal.nl/nederlandse-oorlogs-fanta/ Peter Zwaal, ''Nederlandse oorlogs-Fanta'', 2015]</ref>\n\nFanta production was discontinued when the German and Dutch Coca-Cola branches were reunited with their parent company. Following the launch of several drinks by the Pepsi corporation in the 1950s, Coca-Cola relaunched Fanta in 1955. The drink was heavily marketed in Europe, Asia, Africa, and South America.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/explainer/2010/08/why_do_foreigners_like_fanta_so_much.html|work=Slate|date=August 2010|title=Why do foreigners like Fanta so much}}</ref>\n\nThe orange Fanta of today was produced for the first time in [[Italy]], in [[Naples]], in 1955, when a local bottling plant started producing it using locally sourced [[Orange (fruit)|oranges]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.de/20170523/fanta-how-the-nazi-era-drink-became-the-world-famous-brand|title=How Fanta was invented in Nazi Germany to quench people's thirst for Coke|date=2017-05-23|website=www.thelocal.de|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sibeg.it/en/prodotti/sparkling-drinks/fanta.html|title=Sparkling drinks: Fanta - Sibeg|website=www.sibeg.it|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coca-colaitalia.it/storie/fanta-e-arancia-un-matrimonio-allitaliana|title=Fanta e arancia, un matrimonio all\u2019italiana|website=The Coca-Cola Company|language=it-IT|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref>\n\n== Marketing ==\n[[File:Fanta-Shokata.jpg|thumb|upright|Fanta Shokata with labels upside down as part of the \"turn the world upside down\" ad campaign<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universalmedia.rs/en/caseFanta.html |title=UM fanta shokata |publisher=Universal Media |access-date=2012-09-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127124851/http://www.universalmedia.rs/en/caseFanta.html |archive-date=2014-11-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>]]\n\n=== United States ===\nFanta is known for its upbeat colorful advertising; in the United States, it showcases [[The Fantanas]], a group of young female models, each of whom promotes an individual Fanta flavor. For the re-introduction of Fanta in the United States, Coca-Cola worked with the ad agency [[Ogilvy & Mather|Ogilvy]] (NYC) in 2001. After a brainstorming session, the Ogilvy creative team of Andrea Scaglione, Andrew Ladden and Bill Davaris created the tagline \"Wanta Fanta!\" which became the jingle for the Fantanas in the broadcast campaign. The campaign lasted from mid-2001, in the form of a successful trial run, to October 1, 2006. Three years later, in June 2009, Fanta re-launched the campaign.\n\n=== Germany ===\n==== 75th anniversary version====\nIn February 2015, a 75th-anniversary version of Fanta was released in Germany. Packaged in glass bottles evoking the original design and with an authentic original wartime flavor including 30% whey and pomace, it is described on the packaging as \"less sweet\" and a German original. An associated television ad referenced the history of the drink and said the Coca-Cola company wanted to bring back \"the feeling of the Good Old Times\" which was interpreted by many to mean Nazi rule. The ad was subsequently replaced.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.aol.co.uk/2015/03/05/coca-cola-pulls-german-fanta-ad-over-nazi-controversy|work=AOL Money|date=Mar 5, 2015|\ntitle=Coca-Cola pulls German Fanta ad over Nazi controversy}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2015/03/03/coke-fanta-ad/|title=Coke pulls Fanta ad over Nazi controversy|last=Snyder|first=Benjamin|date=3 March 2015|work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== International availability ==\n{{Main|International availability of Fanta}}\n[[File:FantaChina.jpg|thumb|Variations of Fanta or ''F\u0113nd\u00e1'' (\u82ac\u8fbe) in the Chinese market.]]\nThere are more than 90 flavors worldwide.\n\nIn Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Poland, Serbia, Turkey, Romania, Sweden and some other countries, there is ''Fanta Shokata'' (a wordplay between ''\"soc\"'' which is \"elderberry\" in Romanian, and \"shock\") based on an [[Elderberry|elderflower]] blossom extract drink.\n\nOrange Fanta is available in Canada. The formula differs from its American counterpart in that it contains orange juice<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coca-cola.ca/brands/fanta/fanta-orange|title=Fanta Orange|publisher=|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref> and the American version contains none.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smartlabel.coca-colaproductfacts.com/servlet.049000014235.html|title=Fanta Orange - SmartLabel\u2122|website=smartlabel.coca-colaproductfacts.com|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref> The other variants available in Canada are Grape and Cream Soda, both made with grape juice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coca-cola.ca/brands/fanta/fanta-grape|title=Fanta Grape|publisher=|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coca-cola.ca/brands/fanta/fanta-cream-soda|title=Fanta Cream Soda|publisher=|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrimary competitors to Fanta have included [[Tango (drink)|Tango]], [[Mirinda]], [[Sunkist (soft drink)|Sunkist]], [[Slice (soft drink)|Slice]], [[Sumol]], [[Crush (beverage)|Crush]], [[Faygo]], [[Tropicana Twister]], and [[Orangina]]. Fanta is the second drink to have been produced by Coca-Cola, after the original Coca-Cola.\n\nIn New Zealand, unlike the rest of Australasia, Fanta is visually branded with the original logo used since 2008. The New Zealand market includes the Fanta variants Fanta Blueberry, Fanta Sour Watermelon, and Fanta Strawberry Sherbet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coca-colajourney.co.nz/brands/fanta|title=The Coca-Cola Company Brands: Fanta|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe comedian Fluffy has made references to Fanta having a substantial fan base in India and Mexico.  (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ux8GZAtCN-M&list=RDux8GZAtCN-M&start_radio=1&t=15, Minute 2:21)\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Minute Maid]]\n* [[Hi-C]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bc5QU-DCtUE|title=Why Coca-Cola Invented Fanta In Nazi Germany|publisher=[[Business Insider]]|date=2019-11-08}}\n* {{cite web|title=Coca Cola and the war|url=http://www.diggerhistory.info/pages-food/coca_cola.htm|website=Digger History}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060415021537/http://www.virtualvender.coca-cola.com/ft/detail.jsp?brand_id=258 Fanta on Coca-Cola.com]\n* [http://legacy.signonsandiego.com/news/business/20050513-1029-food-coke.html Coke phasing out Minute Maid soft drinks]\n{{Coca-Cola}}\n{{citrus sodas}}\n\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1940]]\n[[Category:Coca-Cola brands]]\n[[Category:Fruit sodas]]\n[[Category:German inventions of the Nazi period]]\n[[Category:Orange sodas]]\n[[Category:German drinks]]\n[[Category:1940 in Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Short description|Brand of carbonated drinks}} \n{{Use American English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox Beverage\n|name= Fanta\n|image= File:Logo Fanta 2016.png\n|caption= \n|manufacturer= [[The Coca-Cola Company]]\n|origin= [[Germany]] (beverage)<!-- Not \"Nazi\", see [[Talk:Fanta|Fanta talk page]]. --><br />[[Italy]] (orange version)\n|headquarters= \n|introduced= {{start date and age|1940}}\n|variants= See [[Fanta#International availability|International availability]]\n|related= [[Sunkist (soft drink)|Sunkist]], [[Crush (soft drink)|Crush]], [[Slice (soft drink)|Slice]], [[Mirinda]], [[Tango (drink)|Tango]], [[Bluna]].\n}}\n\n'''Fanta''' is a brand of fruit-flavored carbonated drinks created by [[The Coca-Cola Company|Coca-Cola Deutschland]] under the leadership of German businessman [[Max Keith]]. There are more than [[International availability of Fanta|100 flavors worldwide]]. Fanta originated as a [[Coca-Cola]] substitute during the American [[trade embargo]] of [[Nazi Germany]] which affected the availability of Coca-Cola ingredients in 1940; the current version was created in Italy. The name Fanta is a shortening of the word Fantasie (German for fantasy).\n\n==Origin in Germany==\n[[File:FantaKlassik.JPG|thumb|upright|75th anniversary release of Fanta in Germany]]\n\nDuring the [[World War II|Second World War]], the US established a trade embargo against [[Germany]]\u2014making the export of [[Coca-Cola]] syrup difficult.<ref name=\"a\">{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/cokelore/fanta.asp |title=The Reich Stuff? |author=Mikkelson, Barbara |date=April 29, 2011 |work=[[Snopes]] |publisher= |accessdate=March 11, 2012}}</ref> To circumvent this, [[Max Keith]], the head of Coca-Cola Deutschland (Coca-Cola GmbH), decided to create a new product for the German market, using only ingredients available in Germany at the time, including [[beet sugar]], [[whey]], and apple [[pomace]]\u2014the \"leftovers of leftovers\", as Keith later recalled.<ref name=\"a\" /><ref name=\"pendergrast\">[[Mark Pendergrast]]: For God, Country and Coca-Cola, Charles Scribner's Sons, New York, 1993</ref> The name was the result of a brainstorming session, which started with Keith's exhorting his team to \"use their imagination\" (''Fantasie'' in German), to which one of his salesmen, Joe Knipp, retorted \"Fanta!\".<ref name=\"pendergrast\" />\n\nThe plant was cut off from Coca-Cola headquarters during the war. After the war, The Coca-Cola Company regained control of the plant, formula, and the trademarks to the new Fanta product\u2014as well as the plant profits made during the war.<ref name=a /><ref name=\"pendergrast\" />\n\nIn 1943 alone, 3 million cases of Fanta were sold. Many bottles were not drunk, but used to add sweetness and flavor to soups and stews, since wartime sugar was severely rationed.<ref name=a /><ref name=\"pendergrast\" />\n\nDuring the war the Dutch Coca-Cola plant in [[Amsterdam]] (N.V. Nederlandsche Coca-Cola Maatschappij) suffered the same difficulties as the German Coca-Cola plant. Max Keith put the Fanta brand at the disposal of the Dutch Coca-Cola plant, of which he had been appointed the official caretaker. Dutch Fanta had a different recipe from German Fanta, [[Elderberry|elderberries]] being one of the main ingredients.<ref>[http://peterzwaal.nl/nederlandse-oorlogs-fanta/ Peter Zwaal, ''Nederlandse oorlogs-Fanta'', 2015]</ref>\n\nFanta production was discontinued when the German and Dutch Coca-Cola branches were reunited with their parent company. Following the launch of several drinks by the Pepsi corporation in the 1950s, Coca-Cola relaunched Fanta in 1955. The drink was heavily marketed in Europe, Asia, Africa, and South America.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/explainer/2010/08/why_do_foreigners_like_fanta_so_much.html|work=Slate|date=August 2010|title=Why do foreigners like Fanta so much}}</ref>\n\nThe orange Fanta of today was produced for the first time in [[Italy]], in [[Naples]], in 1955, when a local bottling plant started producing it using locally sourced [[Orange (fruit)|oranges]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.de/20170523/fanta-how-the-nazi-era-drink-became-the-world-famous-brand|title=How Fanta was invented in Nazi Germany to quench people's thirst for Coke|date=2017-05-23|website=www.thelocal.de|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sibeg.it/en/prodotti/sparkling-drinks/fanta.html|title=Sparkling drinks: Fanta - Sibeg|website=www.sibeg.it|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coca-colaitalia.it/storie/fanta-e-arancia-un-matrimonio-allitaliana|title=Fanta e arancia, un matrimonio all\u2019italiana|website=The Coca-Cola Company|language=it-IT|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref>\n\n== Marketing ==\n[[File:Fanta-Shokata.jpg|thumb|upright|Fanta Shokata with labels upside down as part of the \"turn the world upside down\" ad campaign<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universalmedia.rs/en/caseFanta.html |title=UM fanta shokata |publisher=Universal Media |access-date=2012-09-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127124851/http://www.universalmedia.rs/en/caseFanta.html |archive-date=2014-11-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>]]\n\n=== United States ===\nFanta is known for its upbeat colorful advertising; in the United States, it showcases [[The Fantanas]], a group of young female models, each of whom promotes an individual Fanta flavor. For the re-introduction of Fanta in the United States, Coca-Cola worked with the ad agency [[Ogilvy & Mather|Ogilvy]] (NYC) in 2001. After a brainstorming session, the Ogilvy creative team of Andrea Scaglione, Andrew Ladden and Bill Davaris created the tagline \"Wanta Fanta!\" which became the jingle for the Fantanas in the broadcast campaign. The campaign lasted from mid-2001, in the form of a successful trial run, to October 1, 2006. Three years later, in June 2009, Fanta re-launched the campaign.\n\n=== Germany ===\n==== 75th anniversary version====\nIn February 2015, a 75th-anniversary version of Fanta was released in Germany. Packaged in glass bottles evoking the original design and with an authentic original wartime flavor including 30% whey and pomace, it is described on the packaging as \"less sweet\" and a German original. An associated television ad referenced the history of the drink and said the Coca-Cola company wanted to bring back \"the feeling of the Good Old Times\" which was interpreted by many to mean Nazi rule. The ad was subsequently replaced.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.aol.co.uk/2015/03/05/coca-cola-pulls-german-fanta-ad-over-nazi-controversy|work=AOL Money|date=Mar 5, 2015|\ntitle=Coca-Cola pulls German Fanta ad over Nazi controversy}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2015/03/03/coke-fanta-ad/|title=Coke pulls Fanta ad over Nazi controversy|last=Snyder|first=Benjamin|date=3 March 2015|work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== International availability ==\n{{Main|International availability of Fanta}}\n[[File:FantaChina.jpg|thumb|Variations of Fanta or ''F\u0113nd\u00e1'' (\u82ac\u8fbe) in the Chinese market.]]\nThere are more than 90 flavors worldwide.\n\nIn Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Poland, Serbia, Turkey, Romania, Sweden and some other countries, there is ''Fanta Shokata'' (a wordplay between ''\"soc\"'' which is \"elderberry\" in Romanian, and \"shock\") based on an [[Elderberry|elderflower]] blossom extract drink.\n\nOrange Fanta is available in Canada. The formula differs from its American counterpart in that it contains orange juice<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coca-cola.ca/brands/fanta/fanta-orange|title=Fanta Orange|publisher=|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref> and the American version contains none.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smartlabel.coca-colaproductfacts.com/servlet.049000014235.html|title=Fanta Orange - SmartLabel\u2122|website=smartlabel.coca-colaproductfacts.com|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref> The other variants available in Canada are Grape and Cream Soda, both made with grape juice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coca-cola.ca/brands/fanta/fanta-grape|title=Fanta Grape|publisher=|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coca-cola.ca/brands/fanta/fanta-cream-soda|title=Fanta Cream Soda|publisher=|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrimary competitors to Fanta have included [[Tango (drink)|Tango]], [[Mirinda]], [[Sunkist (soft drink)|Sunkist]], [[Slice (soft drink)|Slice]], [[Sumol]], [[Crush (beverage)|Crush]], [[Faygo]], [[Tropicana Twister]], and [[Orangina]]. Fanta is the second drink to have been produced by Coca-Cola, after the original Coca-Cola.\n\nIn New Zealand, unlike the rest of Australasia, Fanta is visually branded with the original logo used since 2008. The New Zealand market includes the Fanta variants Fanta Blueberry, Fanta Sour Watermelon, and Fanta Strawberry Sherbet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coca-colajourney.co.nz/brands/fanta|title=The Coca-Cola Company Brands: Fanta|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Minute Maid]]\n* [[Hi-C]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bc5QU-DCtUE|title=Why Coca-Cola Invented Fanta In Nazi Germany|publisher=[[Business Insider]]|date=2019-11-08}}\n* {{cite web|title=Coca Cola and the war|url=http://www.diggerhistory.info/pages-food/coca_cola.htm|website=Digger History}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060415021537/http://www.virtualvender.coca-cola.com/ft/detail.jsp?brand_id=258 Fanta on Coca-Cola.com]\n* [http://legacy.signonsandiego.com/news/business/20050513-1029-food-coke.html Coke phasing out Minute Maid soft drinks]\n{{Coca-Cola}}\n{{citrus sodas}}\n\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1940]]\n[[Category:Coca-Cola brands]]\n[[Category:Fruit sodas]]\n[[Category:German inventions of the Nazi period]]\n[[Category:Orange sodas]]\n[[Category:German drinks]]\n[[Category:1940 in Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Smurgai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInternational availability:Adding a reference made to Fanta in Popular Culture.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fanta"}
